    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Does China Deserve Trade Status?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Bayard K Fetler letter says main effect of granting China permanent normal trading status is to remove yearly debate in Congress</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''2 Congress Panels Strongly Endorse China Trade Bill'' (front page, May 18):</p>
        <p>Granting China permanent normal trading privileges may not significantly affect actual trade with China, since Congress usually grants China trade status every year and would most likely continue to do so in the future.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''2 Congress Panels Strongly Endorse China Trade Bill'' (front page, May 18):</p>
        <p>Granting China permanent normal trading privileges may not significantly affect actual trade with China, since Congress usually grants China trade status every year and would most likely continue to do so in the future.</p>
        <p>The main effect of granting permanent normal trading privileges to China is to remove the yearly debate in Congress over whether or not to grant it trade status and the accompanying public commentary on China's human rights record. This is precisely why it has been left as a yearly exercise in Congress, and should remain so. We have coddled authoritarian governments before, both for economic and strategic reasons, but this does not necessarily lead to improvements in their societies.</p>
        <p>BAYARD K. FETLER  Belmont, Calif., May 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
